#Question 2
#We don't calculate mean, median, sample standard deviation, and coefficient of variation for binary variables because they are qualitative. The following table only shows the descriptive of quantitative variables.

data <- read_excel("E:/School GGU/MSBA 320/MIdterm/FacebookFriends.xlsx")
col.num <- c("Sample", "Age", "Photos", "Albums", "Posts", "Replies", "Children", "Likes", "Events", "Friends")
data[col.num] <- sapply(data[col.num], as.integer)


col.num_binary <- c("Gender", "Emp", "Profile", "Cover", "Orientation", "Relationship", "Edu")
data[col.num_binary] <- sapply(data[col.num_binary], as.factor)


coeffecient_of_variation <- function(x,y){
  cv <- 100 * x/y
  return(cv)
}

b <- c('mean','median','Sample standard deviation','coeffiecent of variation(%)')
c <- c(mean(data$Sample),median(data$Sample),sqrt(var(data$Sample)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Sample)),mean(data$Sample)))
d <- c(mean(data$Age),median(data$Age),sqrt(var(data$Age)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Age)),mean(data$Age)))
e <- c(mean(data$Photos),median(data$Photos),sqrt(var(data$Photos)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Photos)),mean(data$Photos)))

g <- c(mean(data$Albums),median(data$Albums),sqrt(var(data$Albums)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Albums)),mean(data$Albums)))
h <- c(mean(data$Posts),median(data$Posts),sqrt(var(data$Posts)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Posts)),mean(data$Posts)))
i <- c(mean(data$Replies),median(data$Replies),sqrt(var(data$Replies)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Replies)),mean(data$Replies)))
j <- c(mean(data$Children),median(data$Children),sqrt(var(data$Children)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Children)),mean(data$Children)))
k <- c(mean(data$Likes),median(data$Likes),sqrt(var(data$Likes)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Likes)),mean(data$Likes)))
l <- c(mean(data$Events),median(data$Events),sqrt(var(data$Events)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Events)),mean(data$Events)))
m <- c(mean(data$Friends),median(data$Friends),sqrt(var(data$Friends)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Friends)),mean(data$Friends)))

# Join the variables to create a data frame
df <- data.frame(b,c,d,e,g,h,i)
df2 <- data.frame(b,j,k,l,m)
names(df) <- c('Descriptive_Statistic','Sample','Age', 'Photos', 'Albums', 'Posts', 'Replies')
names(df2) <- c('Descriptive_Statistic', 'Children', 'Likes', 'Events', 'Friends')

#since we want to get an idea about the distribution, we will use binary variable as numeric type and calculate the mean, median, standard deviation and coefficient of variation.

data <- read_excel("E:/School GGU/MSBA 320/MIdterm/FacebookFriends.xlsx")

col.num_binary <- c("Gender", "Emp", "Profile", "Cover", "Orientation", "Relationship", "Edu")
data[col.num_binary] <- sapply(data[col.num_binary], as.integer)

coeffecient_of_variation <- function(x,y){
  cv <- 100 * x/y
  return(cv)
}

b <- c('mean','median','Sample standard deviation','coeffiecent of variation(%)')
c <- c(mean(data$Gender),median(data$Gender),sqrt(var(data$Gender)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Gender)),mean(data$Gender)))
d <- c(mean(data$Emp),median(data$Emp),sqrt(var(data$Emp)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Emp)),mean(data$Emp)))
e <- c(mean(data$Profile),median(data$Profile),sqrt(var(data$Profile)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Profile)),mean(data$Profile)))
f <- c(mean(data$Cover),median(data$Cover),sqrt(var(data$Cover)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Cover)),mean(data$Cover)))
g <- c(mean(data$Orientation),median(data$Orientation),sqrt(var(data$Orientation)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Orientation)),mean(data$Orientation)))
h <- c(mean(data$Relationship),median(data$Relationship),sqrt(var(data$Relationship)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Relationship)),mean(data$Relationship)))
i <- c(mean(data$Edu),median(data$Edu),sqrt(var(data$Edu)),coeffecient_of_variation(sqrt(var(data$Edu)),mean(data$Edu)))
# Join the variables to create a data frame
df <- data.frame(b,c,d,e,f,g)
df2 <- data.frame(b,h,i)

names(df) <- c('Descriptive_Statistic','Gender', 'Emp', 'Profile', 'Cover', 'Orientation')
names(df2) <- c('Descriptive_Statistic', 'Relationship', 'Edu')

#1. Sample variable is approximately symmetrically distributed with approximately 57% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately symmetric distribution because the mean and the median is the same. There are more than half data points around the mean.

#2. Age variable is approximately symmetrically distributed with approximately 30% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately symmetric distribution because the mean and the median are approximately the same. There is less number of data points around the mean.

#3. Photos variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 175% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.

#4. No_Of_Tags variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 175% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.

#5. Albums variable is approximately symmetrically distributed with approximately 120% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately symmetric distribution because the mean and the median are approximately the same. All of the data points are highly around the mean.

#6. Posts variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 240% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.

#7. Replies variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 240% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.
    
#According to table 3,
#8.  Children variable is symmetrically distributed with approximately 310% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately symmetric distribution because the mean and the median are the same. All of the data points are highly around the mean. This variable approximately have a standard normal distribution since mean is 0 and the standard deviation is approximately 1.

#9.  Likes variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 180% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.

#10. Events variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 270% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.

#11. Friends variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 86% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. There are more than half data points around the mean.
    
#12. Gender variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 96% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately negatively skewed distribution because the mean is less than the median. Approximately all data points are around the mean.

#13. Emp variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 58% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately negatively skewed distribution because the mean is less than the median. Less number of data points are around the mean.

#14.  Profile variable is symmetrically distributed with approximately 30% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately symmetric distribution because the mean and the median are the same. All of the data points are highly around the mean. This variable approximately have a standard normal distribution since mean is 0 and the standard deviation is approximately 1.

#15. Covers variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 96% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately negatively skewed distribution because the mean is less than the median. Approximately all data points are around the mean.

#16. Orientation variable is symmetrically distributed with approximately 30% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately symmetric distribution because the mean and the median are the same. All of the data points are highly around the mean. This variable approximately have a standard normal distribution since mean is 0 and the standard deviation is approximately 1.
#17. Relationship variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 100% coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.

#18. Edu variable is asymmetrically distributed with approximately 165% of the coefficient of variation. There is an approximately positively skewed distribution because the mean is greater than the median. All of the data points are highly around the mean.
